The paper deals with computational geometry and graph theory, specifically the problem of cutting a polyhedral manifold surface into a single topological disk. This problem is related to computational geometry (cs.CG) as it involves manipulating geometric objects. The paper also discusses algorithms and complexity, which are topics in data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The problem of cutting a surface into a disk is also related to graph theory (cs.GT) as it involves finding a minimum cut graph. Finally, the paper discusses approximation algorithms, which are a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC).
